    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\n\nno\n\n### Feature description\n\nIn [indent-blankline](https://github.com/lukas-reineke/indent-blankline.nvim) which uses virtual text to show line indents there's a tension between needing to suppress gui options that set italics/underline to avoid fudging the indention's virtual text while also wanting to allow mixing other gui elements that could have been set by the theme (f.ex. gui=reverse used for block selections).\r\n\r\nThis came up in this bug where the need to suppress the italics/bold conflicted with the theme: https://github.com/lukas-reineke/indent-blankline.nvim/issues/328\r\n\r\nThe [plugin author suggests](https://github.com/lukas-reineke/indent-blankline.nvim/issues/328#issuecomment-983345907) neovim could add negative gui options e.g. `noitalic` to resolve this tension and allow correctly expressing what indent-blankline is trying to accomplish without breaking theming.\r\n\r\n> So a highlight group can set this, all gui options get combined, but `noitalic` overwrites if the underlying highlight group had `italic`",
